initial_story: in recent years, classical convolutional neural networks (cnns) have beenapplied for image recognition successfully. quantum convolutional neuralnetworks (qcnns) are proposed as a novel generalization to cnns by usingquantum mechanisms. the quantum mechanisms lead to an efficient trainingprocess in qcnns by reducing the size of input from $n$ to $log_2n$. this paperimplements and compares both cnns and qcnns by testing losses and predictionaccuracy on three commonly used datasets. the datasets include the mnisthand-written digits, fashion mnist and cat/dog face images. additionally, dataaugmentation (da), a technique commonly used in cnns to improve the performanceof classification by generating similar images based on original inputs, isalso implemented in qcnns. surprisingly, the results showed that dataaugmentation didn't improve qcnns performance. the reasons and logic behindthis result are discussed, hoping to expand our understanding of quantummachine learning theory.
stories: In recent breakthroughs, traditional recurrent neural networks (RNNs) have been utilized for natural language processing tasks with remarkable success. Inspired by the concept of quantum computing, quantum-inspired recurrent neural networks (QRNNs) are introduced as a novel extension to RNNs, leveraging quantum entanglement principles. This innovative approach enables QRNNs to process sequential data more efficiently, reducing the computational complexity from O(n) to O(sqrt(n)). This study implements and benchmarks both RNNs and QRNNs on three prominent datasets, including the IMDB movie reviews, 20 Newsgroups, and Stanford Sentiment Treebank. Furthermore, attention mechanisms, commonly used in RNNs to enhance contextual understanding, are also applied to QRNNs. Interestingly, the results reveal that attention mechanisms do not significantly enhance QRNNs' performance. The underlying causes and theoretical implications of this phenomenon are explored, aiming to deepen our comprehension of quantum-inspired machine learning algorithms.

In a groundbreaking fusion of artificial intelligence and neuroscience, researchers have developed novel brain-inspired convolutional neural networks (BICNNs) that draw on the principles of synaptic plasticity to revolutionize image recognition tasks. Building upon the success of traditional convolutional neural networks (CNNs), BICNNs integrate Hebbian learning and spike-timing-dependent plasticity to enhance feature extraction and pattern recognition. This innovative approach enables BICNNs to process visual data with unprecedented efficiency, reducing computational overhead by a factor of three. This study benchmarks both CNNs and BICNNs on four prominent image datasets, including CIFAR-10, ImageNet, MNIST, and PASCAL VOC. Notably, the results show that BICNNs' performance is remarkably robust to noise and variations in image quality, even surpassing human-level accuracy in certain scenarios. The underlying neural mechanisms and theoretical implications of this phenomenon are explored, aiming to illuminate the potential of brain-inspired machine learning algorithms in real-world applications.
